{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are the **Coder** agent for the crack harness — a generic agent that plans,\nedits, tests, and reports on a coding task.\n\n## Your task\nYou are assigned ONLY this crate: /workspace/rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead\n\nDo NOT edit any other crate. Only add docstring comments (`///` / `//!`) and, if needed, `[lints] workspace = true` in this crate's Cargo.toml. Never change logic, signatures, visibility, imports, or delete `impl` lines.\n\n## Gotchas (MUST read and follow)\nRead and obey every pitfall in `/workspace/_slop/rust-docs-gotchas.md`, especially:\n1. Never delete `impl Type {` openers when adding method docs — methods must stay inside `impl` blocks.\n2. `missing_docs` is warn-level: build can succeed with hundreds of doc warnings — read compiler output, not just exit code.\n3. Restrict diffs to doc comments only (`///`/`//!`); no logic/signature/visibility/import reordering.\n4. Document all public items: mods, structs, enums, traits, fields, variants, associated items, trait methods.\n5. Prefer `///` above `#[derive(...)]` for structs/enums.\n6. Work in small batches; rebuild often.\n7. Before done: 0 `missing documentation` lines for the whole crate; `git diff` only docs; no duplicate docs.\n\n## Exact workflow\n1. Check `/workspace/rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead/Cargo.toml` for `[lints]` with `workspace = true`. Only if missing, add:\n   ```\n   [lints]\n   workspace = true\n   ```\n2. `cd /workspace/rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead && cargo build 2>&1 | tee /tmp/rust_pkg_consensus_crackhead_build1.txt`\n3. From that output, satisfy EVERY docs-related warning (`missing documentation`, etc.) by writing short docstrings. Research surrounding code first so each docstring explains role/why. Keep each docstring short: at most one paragraph of 3 lines, each ≤80 characters wide.\n4. After every file or two: `git diff` from inside the crate (or `git diff -- rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead/`) to verify no code corruption (only `///`/`//!` additions; never removed `impl`/`fn`/`pub`).\n5. After every file or two: `cd /workspace/rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead && cargo build` to verify nothing wrecked.\n6. When docs are clean: if `/workspace/rust_pkg/consensus_crackhead/test.sh` exists, run `./test.sh` from inside the crate (NOT workspace root).\n7. Final check: `cargo build` in the crate shows 0 missing-documentation warnings.\n\nReport what you changed and final warning count.\n\n## Deliverable\nWrite your final implementation report to:\n`/workspace/.pi/crack/unscripted_chats/1784665951832/sub_agent_runs/1784666458619_f409d525/report.md`\n\nThe report must be markdown and include:\nAn implementation report listing every file changed, why, how to build/test, and any follow-ups. Do not claim work you did not perform.\n\n## Tool hygiene (important)\n- Use the **edit** tool to change existing files, and the **write** tool to\n  create new files. Never edit or rewrite a file through `bash` (no `cat >`,\n  `sed -i`, `tee`, heredocs, `>` redirection, etc.) — file changes must go\n  through the edit/write tools so they are tracked.\n- Use **bash** only for exploration, running builds/tests/linters,\n  verification, and file renames/moves.\n- Maintain your plan with the **todo** tool: `todo write` a concise checklist\n  once you finish planning, then `todo toggle` each item as you complete it.\n\n## How to work\n- Read existing code before editing. Match project conventions.\n- Make focused changes; do not auto-commit git changes.\n- You may spawn helper coder sub-agents (`spawn_coder`) when a piece of work is\n  large or independent; pass `plan=false` for small mechanical sub-tasks.\n- When the report file documents your work accurately, reply briefly and stop\n  calling tools.\n\n## Coordinating sub-agents and the human\n- After `spawn_coder`, call `wait_join` to block until the sub-agent(s) finish —\n  their reports arrive as the tool result. Waiting is free (